{{For|information on the administrative structure of Wikipedia|Wikipedia:Administration}} {{Infobox book | name = How Wikipedia Works | image = hww-cover.jpg | caption = | author = Phoebe Ayers, Charles Matthews, Ben Yates | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = | genre = [[Reference]] | publisher = [[No Starch Press]] | pub_date = 2008 | media_type = paperback | isbn = 1-59327-176-X | dewey = 030 22 | congress = AE1.5 .A98 2008 | oclc = 185698411 | website = http://www.howwikipediaworks.net/ }}
'''''How Wikipedia Works''''' is a 2009 book by Phoebe Ayers, Charles Matthews, and Ben Yates. It is a [[how-to]] reference for using and contributing to the [[Wikipedia]] encyclopedia, targeted at "students, professors, and everyday experts and fans". It offers specific sections for teachers, users, and researchers.<ref name="review">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090124083459/http://1776productions.com/SBR_October_08.pdf Book review] in the ''Sacramento Book Review'', Vol. 1 Iss. 2, October, 2008, p.19.</ref>
''How Wikipedia Works (And How You Can Be a Part of It)'' is published by [[No Starch Press]], part of their series of technical how-to books. ''[[The Register]] (UK)'' called it "a great one-stop source for information of the world’s go-to source for information."<ref name="Reg">[https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/10/07/regbooks_wikipedia_200810/ How Wikipedia Works], a review by the Geek Guide<sub>2</sub>, October 7, 2008</ref> The book was originally published under the [[GNU Free Documentation License]]. At the time of publication, Wikipedia was also released under the GFDL. The book has since been re-licensed under the [[Creative Commons License|CC BY-SA]], which Wikipedia now uses.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Wikipedia Works|url=http://www.howwikipediaworks.net/|accessdate=4 July 2014}}</ref> It was designed as a reference work and has detailed bibliographies for each section.
