The '''Quebec Gay Archives''' ({{lang-fr|'''Archives gaies du Québec'''}}) is a [[nonprofit]] organization dedicated to documenting the history of the [[LGBT|gay and lesbian]] communities of the Canadian province of [[Quebec]].<ref name="YU"/> Founded in 1983 and located in [[Montreal]],<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite news | author =Richard Burnett | title =Gay Archives to stage blow out| publisher =Hour.ca | date =June 12, 2008 | url =http://www.hour.ca/news/news.aspx?iIDArticle=14875 | accessdate=2009-04-03}}</ref> the QGA maintains collections of periodicals, newspapers, press clippings, book, videocassettes, DVDs, posters, photos and archival materials.<ref name=YU>{{cite news|author= |title=Gay and Lesbian Studies Research Guide |publisher=Yale University Library |date= |url=http://www.library.yale.edu/rsc/gayles/gaylib.html |accessdate=2009-04-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908120207/http://www.library.yale.edu/rsc/gayles/gaylib.html |archivedate=September 8, 2008 }}</ref> Its collection includes the photographic canon of Alan B. Stone, which reflects the life's work of the notable Montreal "[[beefcake]]" photographer,<ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite news | author =Matthew Hays | title =Flesh for Fantasy| publisher =CBC News | date =May 2, 2006 | url =http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/2006/05/02/alan-stone-beefcake.html | accessdate=2009-04-03}}</ref> as well as one of the few surviving copies of the historic LGBT publication ''[[Les Mouches Fantastiques]]''.
