{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Globe'' (London newspaper)}}
[[File:The Globe placard Versailles peace signed 28 June 1919.jpg|thumb|right|<center>Placard for ''The Globe'' announcing the signing of the [[Treaty of Versailles]], 28 June 1919</center>]]
'''''The Globe''''' was a British newspaper which ran from 1803 to 1921. It was  founded by [[Christopher Blackett]],<ref>''Timothy Hackworth and the Locomotive'' by Robert Young page 53 says of Blackett "Better known in London as the proprietor of the ''Globe'' newspaper, established in 1803". Young was published in 1923 and 1975.  It is likely that Young sources subsequent quoted references to this linkage.</ref><ref>''Blackett's and Literature'' at http://www.theblacketts.com/articles/47-blacketts-and-literature retrieved 7 November 2013.</ref> the coal mining entrepreneur from Wylam Northumberland who commissioned the first commercially useful [[adhesion]] steam locomotives in the world.<ref>"Timothy Hackworth's Essential Place in Early Locomotive Development", an article by Norman Hill in '' Railway Archive Number 16'', Lightmoor Press, Witney, 2007 page 6.</ref> It merged with the ''[[Pall Mall Gazette]]'' in 1921. Under the ownership of [[Robert Torrens (economist)|Robert Torrens]] during the 1820s it supported [[Radicalism (historical)|radical]] politics, and had a reputation associating it closely with [[Jeremy Bentham]]. By the 1840s it was more mainstream, and received briefings from within the Whig administration. In 1871 it was owned by a Tory group headed by [[George Cubitt]], who brought in [[Sir George Armstrong, 1st Baronet|George Armstrong]] as editor.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=30449|title=Armstrong, Sir George Carlyon Hughes, first baronet (1836–1907)|first=H. C. G.|last=Matthew}}</ref> It was controlled shortly before [[World War I]] by [[Max Aitken]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=30358|title=Aitken, William Maxwell|first=D. George|last=Boyce}}</ref>

==Staff==
Staff of the newspaper included [[Arthur Morrison]], [[William Le Queux]],<ref>[http://www.williamlequeux.com/ Official Publisher Site of William Le Queux] Retrieved 15 October 2013.</ref> and [[P. G. Wodehouse]], who took over from [[William Beach Thomas]] as assistant to [[Harold Begbie]] on the "By the Way" column, which he would eventually take over in 1904, when Begbie left.<ref name=jasen/> Wodehouse's career at the newspaper coincided with those of Charles H. Bovill and [[Herbert Westbrook]].<ref name=jasen>Jasen, David A. (2002) [https://books.google.com/books?id=9L2kjKQ8CvYC&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=charles+h.+bovill&source=bl&ots=mdLRgMmgf7&sig=YEZsLpYg1SLkS3pM3U6j2FFtjts&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NImDT4CjIKiP0QGt_5SrBw&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=bovill&f=false ''P.G. Wodehouse: A Portrait of a Master'', pp. 42–50. Music Sales Group.] Google Books. Retrieved 15 October 2013.</ref> Under Aitken (Beaverbrook) the "By the Way" column was moved to the Daily Express, where it was signed 'Beachcomber'.

